@node iso8859

 ISO 8859 vs. ISO Latin

 HTTP/1.0 uses 8 bit ISO Latin-1 as default encoding: ISO Latin  characters
 can  be  used directly in HTML documents. The Amiga character set conforms
 to ISO Latin. There is nothing wrong with using ISO Latin characters above
 127  (e.g.  "ä")  directly in HTML code.

 You may use the ISO 8859 encoding in HTML documents, too. ISO  8859  is  a
 7-bit  subset  of  ISO  Latin  (a-Z,  numbers, punctuation marks). Special
 symbols are used to describe additional characters. For example,  "&auml;"
 is the symbol for "ä".

 Please note that usage of the ISO 8859  encoding  is  required  for  those
 characters  that  collide  with  HTML  commands  (listed in the menu). For
 example, the character "<" (less than) can not be used  directly  in  text
 since  browsers  assume  that  it starts a HTML command. Usage of ISO 8859
 symbols is optional for all other characters.

 Please note that editors - as opposed to browsers - may or may not conform
 to  the  ISO  Latin  encoding.  For  example,  Win95 editors usually don't
 support the ISO Latin encoding. Converting a text to ISO 8859 solves  this
 problem.

